<br>
The Court's don't like to make law as a general proposition, and are required to limit their involvement in issues as much as possible.  As a result, despite how intriguing the case might be, if the Court has an out on jurisdictional grounds (like here), they are required to take that out.  Dollars to donuts, that's what will take place here. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umitchtheblonde.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mitch The Blonde</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://megablonde.freewebspace.com/rbt-hex.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 3204<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/9/02 3:29:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3442.topic&index=263>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Pledge to our flag, an ad for flag makers?</span><hr size=1> ''If I lived in some of those Middle Eastern countries, I would find it deeply disturbing that I couldn’t kick back with a Playboy or some other form of pr0n anytime I wanted to. But I would also understand that those laws were embedded into their culture before my grandparents were born. If I couldn’t deal with it I would move, not attempt to change the country to fit my beliefs.''<br>
